---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { renderLayers } from '../data/renderLayers.js';
import RenderInvalidation from '../components/RenderInvalidation.svelte';
import EventLoop from '../components/EventLoop.svelte';
import BrowserUi from '../components/BrowserUi.astro';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import SeeAlso from '../components/SeeAlso.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
const L = Object.fromEntries(renderLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — the render pipeline';
const description = 'A deep dive into how the browser turns code into pixels: the DOM tree, computed style, layout, paint, and composite — and why some changes are cheap and others force the whole pipeline.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={renderLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer 19</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>RENDER</em><br />PIPELINE</h1>
    <p class="lede">The browser does this dance up to 60 times a second: turn your HTML and CSS into a tree, compute styles, lay out boxes, paint pixels, and composite layers onto the screen. Touch the wrong property and the whole thing re-runs.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · DOM → style → layout → paint → composite → the event loop</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.R0}>
    <p class="prose">The browser parses your HTML into the <span class="hl">DOM</span> — a live tree of nodes. Tags nest into parent/child relationships; this tree is what CSS targets and what JavaScript reads and mutates.</p>
    <div class="widget">
      <div class="w-label">a snippet of HTML, parsed into a node tree</div>
      <div class="domtree">
        <div class="dom-node">html
          <div class="dom-kids">
            <div class="dom-node">head</div>
            <div class="dom-node">body
              <div class="dom-kids">
                <div class="dom-node">h1 <span class="dom-text">“Hello”</span></div>
                <div class="dom-node">p <span class="dom-text">“…”</span></div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <Takeaway>The DOM is the browser's editable model of the page — a tree, not the text you typed.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="HTML is flat text, but styling, scripting, and rendering all need to know which element is inside which."
      idea="Parse the markup once into a tree of nodes, where nesting is explicit — every later stage operates on this structure."
      tradeoff="The DOM is large and live: touching it can be slow, and frameworks exist largely to batch and minimize DOM work."
      next="An untyled tree isn't enough — every node needs its computed look."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R1}>
    <p class="prose">For every node, the browser resolves which CSS rules apply and who wins — that's the <b>cascade</b>: more specific selectors and later rules override earlier ones. The result is a fully computed style for each element.</p>
    <Takeaway>Style turns "here are some rules" into "here is exactly how this element looks," resolving every conflict by specificity and order.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Many rules can target the same element with conflicting values — there has to be one definite answer per property."
      idea="The cascade ranks declarations by origin, specificity, and source order, then computes one final value for every property on every node."
      tradeoff="Specificity battles and !important wars are the dark side; the same flexibility that makes CSS powerful makes it hard to predict."
      next="A styled node still has no size or position — that's layout."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R2}>
    <p class="prose">Layout (reflow) walks the styled tree and computes <b>geometry</b>: where every box sits and how big it is. Each box is content wrapped in padding, a border, and margin — the <span class="hl">box model</span>.</p>
    <div class="widget">
      <div class="w-label">the box model — every element is boxes inside boxes</div>
      <div class="boxmodel">
        <div class="bm bm-margin"><span class="bm-tag">margin</span>
          <div class="bm bm-border"><span class="bm-tag">border</span>
            <div class="bm bm-padding"><span class="bm-tag">padding</span>
              <div class="bm bm-content">content</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <Takeaway>Layout is geometry: turning "this element exists and is styled" into "it occupies exactly this rectangle."</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Pixels need coordinates, but CSS describes sizes relatively — percentages, flex, auto, content-driven heights."
      idea="Resolve all of that into concrete rectangles by walking the tree, sizing each box and positioning it relative to its neighbours and parent."
      tradeoff="Layout is expensive and global-ish: one changed size can shift everything after it, so reflow is a common performance cost."
      next="Boxes with positions still aren't visible — paint fills them in."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R3}>
    <p class="prose">Paint fills each box with actual pixels — text, colors, borders, shadows — often onto separate <span class="hl">layers</span>. The compositor then assembles those layers into the final frame, usually on the <b>GPU</b>.</p>
    <Takeaway>Paint rasterizes boxes into pixels; compositing stitches the layers into the frame you see.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="A positioned box is still abstract — the screen needs concrete coloured pixels, assembled fast enough for smooth motion."
      idea="Rasterize content into layers, then let the compositor (often the GPU) transform and stack those layers into a frame."
      tradeoff="Layers cost memory, and too many or badly chosen ones hurt instead of help; compositing is fast only because layout and paint already did the hard part."
      next="Not every change needs all of these stages — which is the whole performance game."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R4}>
    <p class="prose">A style change doesn't always re-run everything. Changing geometry (<code>width</code>) forces layout, paint, and composite. A color change skips layout. But <code>transform</code> and <code>opacity</code> only re-composite — the compositor just moves an existing layer.</p>
    <RenderInvalidation client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Animate transform and opacity, not width and top: the cheap properties skip layout and paint entirely.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Janky pages usually come from doing too much per frame — recomputing layout and repainting when it wasn't necessary."
      idea="Know which stage each property invalidates: geometry → layout, appearance → paint, transform/opacity → composite only."
      tradeoff="The cheap path needs its own layer (and the memory that costs), and over-promoting layers can backfire."
      next="But what decides when a frame runs at all? The event loop."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R5}>
    <p class="prose">All that work is driven by one <b>event loop</b>. Each turn: run a <span class="hl">task</span> (a click, a timer) to completion, drain every <span class="hl">microtask</span> (Promises) — then, if a frame is due, run <code>requestAnimationFrame</code> callbacks and render. Rendering and your JavaScript share one thread, so a slow task blocks the frame: that's <b>jank</b>.</p>
    <EventLoop client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The event loop interleaves your JS with rendering on a single thread — microtasks before the next frame, rAF just before paint, and any long task stalls the whole thing.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="os" note="how the OS shares the CPU too — but preemptively, so no single task can freeze it" />
    <Why
      problem="JavaScript and rendering run on one thread, so they must take turns — and the order (and what blocks what) decides whether the UI stays smooth."
      idea="Run one task fully, drain all microtasks, then render at most once per frame; schedule visual work in requestAnimationFrame and defer heavy work off the critical path."
      tradeoff="The single thread keeps the model simple but unforgiving: one long task (or a flood of microtasks) freezes input and animation until it finishes."
      next="Put the pipeline and the loop together and it's one frame, sixty times a second."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.R6}>
    <p class="prose">End to end, every frame: HTML becomes the <b>DOM</b>, CSS computes <b>style</b>, the tree is laid out into boxes, the boxes are <b>painted</b>, and the layers are <b>composited</b> to the screen — then any change kicks off just the stages it touched, again and again.</p>
    <BrowserUi />
    <Takeaway>What you see is the last step of a pipeline the browser re-runs continuously — and the art is making each pass do as little as possible.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Interfaces feel instantaneous, which hides how much repeated work stands between a state change and a pixel."
      idea="Treat rendering as a pipeline run per frame: build, style, layout, paint, composite — each stage handing structure to the next."
      tradeoff="The pipeline buys a declarative, flexible UI model at the cost of performance cliffs when a change forces expensive early stages."
      next="Zoom back out: this is what the main stack's Browser/UI layer is doing at the very top of the climb."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="render" client:visible />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
  /* DOM tree */
  .domtree{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:14px;color:var(--ink);padding:4px 2px}
  .dom-node{padding:3px 0}
  .dom-kids{margin-left:14px;padding-left:14px;border-left:1px solid var(--border)}
  .dom-text{color:var(--violet)}
  /* box model */
  .boxmodel{display:flex;justify-content:center;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px}
  .bm{position:relative;border-radius:8px;padding:26px 18px 14px;text-align:center}
  .bm-tag{position:absolute;top:5px;left:10px;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--faint)}
  .bm-margin{border:1px dashed var(--border);background:rgba(255,180,84,.06)}
  .bm-border{border:1px solid var(--blue);background:var(--blue-d)}
  .bm-padding{border:1px dashed var(--signal);background:var(--signal-d)}
  .bm-content{border:1px solid var(--border-hot);background:var(--surface);padding:18px 28px;color:var(--ink);font-weight:700}
</style>
